ce:section.ce:para:
Identifying the intermediates of the EF process is necessary since the toxicity of the by-products could be even more than the pharmaceutical itself in the aqueous environment. Therefore, in the current study, the intermediates of the TCL removal were investigated and identified via the GC-MS technique. To ease the separation and identification of low volatile and highly stable intermediate compounds in the column, the derivation method was used via N, O-bis (trimethylsilyl) acetamide. GC-MS analysis was carried out after the silylation of the optimum sample. The mass spectra obtained from the GC-MS analysis of the samples were compared with the spectral information in the Wiley 7n software of the GC-MS device. Ten compounds were recognized (Table 7
                        ), including acetamide, propanedioic acid methyl, benzene 1-methyl-2-(1-methylethyl), ethanimidic acid N-methyl, 2-propenoic acid, bicyclo [3.1.0] hexan-3-one-4-methyl-1-(1-methylethyl), oxanilic acid, benzeneacetic acid, decanoic acid, and 1,2-benzenedicarboxylic acid in order of retention time (Rt) at GC-MS column. Fig. 11
                         depicts the suggested TCL removal mechanism via the EF process based on identified GC-MS intermediates. It is possible that ●OH radicals attacked C–C, C=C, C=O, C–O, and C–N bonds. Aromatic compounds may be produced due to partial TCL breakdown at the first 20 min of the EF reaction and further oxidation at the rest of the EF reaction time will result in smaller intermediates. TCL removal produces many linear and short-chain by-products that escape identification owing to the limitations of the analysis. These compounds will finally convert to CO2 and H2O in the latest stages of the EF process.
